{{Infobox basketball biography | name = Sadi Gülçelik | image = | caption = | league = | team_link = | position = | height_m = | weight_kg = | number = | high_school = | years1 = | team1 = [[Galatasaray S.K. (men's basketball)|Galatasaray Basketball]] | years2 = | team2 = Karagücü | years3 = | team3 = Modaspor | nationality = Turkish | birth_date = 22 October 1930 | birth_place = [[İstanbul]], Turkey | death_date = {{death date and age|1980|08|19|1930|10|22|df=y}} | death_place = [[Riyadh]], Saudi Arabia | college = | draft_year = | career_start = | career_end = | highlights = | medaltemplates = }}
'''Sadi Gülçelik''' (22 October 1930&ndash;19 August 1980) was a [[Turkey|Turkish]] [[basketball player]], [[civil engineer]] and entrepreneur.
SadiGülçelik was born in [[Istanbul]], Turkey on 22 October 1930.<ref name="sr"/> He played for [[Galatasaray S.K. (men's volleyball)|Galatasaray Volleyball]] and [[Galatasaray S.K. (men's basketball)|Galatasaray Basketball]], which was nicknamed "The invincible Armada" ({{lang-tr|Yenilmez Armada}}),<ref name="gs"/> Gülçelik was also part of the basketball teams Karagücü and Modaspor.<ref name="p1"/> He participated at the [[Basketball at the 1952 Summer Olympics#Summary|1952 Summer Olympics]] in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]].<ref name="sr"/><ref name="z1"/> He scored 206 points in total for the [[Turkey national basketball team]].<ref name="p1"/>
He graduated from [[İstanbul Technical University]] as a civil engineer and established [[Enka Insaat ve Sanayi A.S.|Enka Construction Co.]] with his brother-in-law [[Şarık Tara]] in 1957.<ref name="enka"/>
Gülçelik died in an [[Saudia Flight 163|air disaster]] in [[Riyadh]], [[Saudi Arabia]] on 19 August 1980.<ref name="sr"/>
A sports complex, Enka Sadi Gülçelik Spor Sitesi, in [[Sarıyer]], Istanbul is named in his honor.<ref name="p1"/><ref name="ise"/>
